The Ministry of Health on Friday announced that 390
people tested positive for COVID-19 from a sample size of 3,353
tested in the last 24 hours, marking a positivity rate of 11.6 per cent. Of the cases, 353 are Kenyans while 37 are foreigners; 202 are females and 188 are males, while the youngest is a
one-year-old child and the oldest is 101 years old. Total confirmed positive cases are now 328,709, while
cumulative tests so far conducted are at 3,717,333. The infections were recorded across the country as follows: Nairobi
274, Kiambu 37, Nakuru 20, Siaya 10, Kilifi 9, Mombasa 8, Murang’a 8, Nyeri 7,
Laikipia 4, Uasin Gishu 3, Bungoma 2, Kisumu 2, Nyamira 2, Busia, Embu, Meru
and Nyandarua had one case each. Health Cabinet Secretary Mutahi Kagwe, in a statement to
newsrooms on Thursday, said 163 patients recovered from the disease; 162 from
the Home-Based and Isolation Care Program while one is from health facilities countrywide.
Total recoveries are now at 320,146. However, no patient succumbed to the disease;
therefore, the cumulative fatalities remain at 5,651. “There are 52 patients currently admitted in our health
facilities, while 2,860 are under the Home-Based Isolation and Care program,”
noted CS Kagwe. “Three patients are in the Intensive Care Unit (ICU) on
supplemental oxygen while seven are in the general wards on supplemental
oxygen. No patient is in the High Dependency Unit (HDU).” On the vaccination exercise, the CS revealed that a
total of 18,551,017 vaccines have been administered across the country. Of
these, 16,630,188 are doses administered to the adult population (18 years
and above) as of June 16, 2022. He further stated that 1,483,574 doses were administered to
those between 15 to 17 years; 38,869 are below 15 years but above 12 years,
while 397,904 are booster doses. He stated that the total number of vaccines administered in
the last 24 hours is 20,287 while the total number of people fully vaccinated
is 7,917.  “Proportion of adults fully vaccinated was 31.4%. The
government is working towards vaccinating a targeted population of 27,246,033,”
added Kagwe.